          "body": "Psalm 136 is unique in the Hebrew Psalter: every single verse carries an identical second half — 'for His lovingkindness is everlasting.' This is not artistic monotony but liturgical architecture. The psalm was designed for antiphonal performance in the Second Temple, with the Levites announcing each act of God and the congregation responding with the refrain. The structural implication is profound: the congregation does not merely hear about *chesed* — they say it twenty-six times, attaching it to twenty-six different acts of God. By the end of the psalm, the community has rehearsed the entire theological shape of their history and confessed the same interpretive verdict over every piece of it. Derek Kidner (Psalms 73-150, TOTC) notes that the very repetitiveness is the point: when faith is under pressure, the mind needs grooves worn deep. The antiphon is the groove."
