          "body": "Most ancient Near Eastern creation accounts are stories of divine conflict — Marduk slays Tiamat, the cosmos emerges from the carcass. Psalm 136 subverts the entire genre. Creation here is not a cosmic battle but an act of covenant love. 'He made the heavens with skill (tavunah)' (v.5), 'He spread out the earth above the waters' (v.6), 'He made the great lights' (v.7) — and after each act, 'His lovingkindness is everlasting.' The sun does not rise because Baal renewed it; it rises because the covenant God who remembered Israel in her low estate is still keeping the morning. Calvin observed that the creation account here is not primarily cosmological but doxological: the psalmist is not explaining how the world was made but why it should be praised. The theological argument is that the same *chesed* that rescued Israel from Egypt was already present at the first day of creation — God's love for His covenant people is woven into the structure of the universe itself."
