          "body": "The psalm spends more verses on the exodus (vv.10-15) than on any other single episode, and the detail is precise: the smiting of the firstborn (v.10), the extraction of Israel from Egypt's midst (v.11), the strong hand and outstretched arm (v.12, the Deuteronomic formula of Deuteronomy 4:34; 5:15; 26:8), the division of the Red Sea (v.13), the safe passage through it (v.14), and the destruction of Pharaoh's army in it (v.15). The granular particularity is intentional: every step of the exodus is an act of *chesed*, not just the headline miracle. Peter Craigie (Psalms 1-50, WBC) notes that the strong hand and outstretched arm formula is covenantal — it is the standard language of YHWH acting as Suzerain on behalf of His vassal. The psalm is claiming that the Sinai covenant relationship is visible in every movement of the exodus, from plague to sea-crossing. The New Testament will read the exodus as the typological template for the greater deliverance accomplished at the cross (1 Corinthians 10:1-4; Hebrews 11:29), which means the psalm's christological resonance is rich for the New Covenant community."
