          "body": "The psalm's most unexpected move is its last before the closing doxology: 'Who gives food to all flesh — for His lovingkindness is everlasting' (v.25). After twenty-four verses cataloguing cosmic creation and national miracles, the psalm ends with groceries. The move is not anticlimactic; it is the psalm's theological climax in miniature. The same lovingkindness that divided the Red Sea is operative in today's ordinary provision for every living creature. The transition to 'all flesh' — not just Israel, not just the covenant community, but every creature that needs to eat — universalizes *chesed* without evacuating its covenantal particularity. God's providential care for every sparrow (Matthew 6:26) and every human stomach is a present-tense enactment of the same everlasting love the psalm has been celebrating. The Lord's Prayer petition 'Give us this day our daily bread' (Matthew 6:11) is, in effect, an application of Psalm 136:25 — asking the God of heaven, whose lovingkindness is everlasting, to continue doing what He has always done."
