        "excerpt": "Give thanks to the LORD, for He is good, for His lovingkindness is everlasting.",
        "body": "The psalm opens not with a narrative but with a threefold imperative addressed to the congregation: give thanks to the LORD, to the God of gods, to the Lord of lords. The three titles are ascending in comprehensiveness. YHWH is the covenant name — personal, historical, the God who rescued and bound Himself to Israel. 'God of gods' (*elohim* over *elohim*) is the supreme deity claim — whatever spiritual powers exist, YHWH towers over them all. 'Lord of lords' (*adon* over *adonim*) is the political supremacy claim — whatever kings and rulers hold sway on earth, they hold sway under Him. This is not mere hyperbole; it is the theological foundation the rest of the psalm requires. Before you can understand why the plagues on Egypt were acts of *chesed*, you need to know that the God who sent them outranks Pharaoh at every level of the cosmic order.\n\nThe reason for thanksgiving is stated with equal economy: 'for He is good.' *Tov* — good, in the most comprehensive Hebrew sense. Not merely kind or benevolent but ontologically, morally, and functionally good. The Hebrew resonance is rich: God declared His creation 'good' (*tov*) in Genesis 1. The Psalter's common refrain 'the LORD is good' (Psalm 100:5; 107:1; 118:1) is not a platitude but a foundational confession that everything God does — including judgment, including wilderness, including the days the congregation does not feel it — issues from a character that is fundamentally, irrevocably good.\n\nThe invocation's function in the psalm's argument is crucial: these three verses say nothing about acts yet. They establish identity. The psalmist insists that Israel must know who YHWH is — and that He is good — before they can interpret anything He has done. Without the identity anchor, the exodus looks like a tribal deity favoring his own. With it, the exodus is the historically specific expression of an everlasting, universally supreme lovingkindness.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yadah* (give thanks) carries the physical connotation of the hand extended in praise — declarative, public acknowledgment, not private sentiment. *Tov* (good) is the same word used of creation's assessment in Genesis 1. *Chesed* and *olam* — the psalm's two load-bearing words — appear together for the first time in v.1 and will never be separated for the remaining twenty-five verses."
